As depicted in the UV–vis spectrum (Fig. 4
                        a), the LB-CDs solution shows an absorption peak at 290 nm, which could be attributed to the n–π* transition of the C=O bond. The fluorescence emission spectrum of LB-CDs exhibits an intensive peak at 448 nm, and the corresponding excitation wavelength is 370 nm. The diluted solution of LB-CDs exhibits a blue color under 365 nm UV light illumination. By contrast, the diluted solution of LB-CDs exhibits a light-yellow color under natural light (Fig. 4a). The QY of the synthetic LB-CDs was measured using quinine sulfate (QY = 54%) as reference, and the measurement result was 17.8%, indicating outstanding fluorescent properties. This value is greater than that of CDs previously stated (Table 1
                        ). Similar to the typical CDs, the developed LB-CDs exhibited excitation-dependent fluorescent properties. As shown in Fig. 4b, when the excitation wavelength increased from 320 nm to 480 nm, the fluorescent peak red-shifted and the most powerful emission spectrum was attained at the excitation wavelength of 370 nm. These findings can be attributed to the various sizes of nano-CDs and the allocation of various surface conditions because of different organic groups on the surface of CDs [39].

Sensitivity is considered one of the most significant parameters used to measure the feasibility of the sensing system. With respect to sensitivity research, the examination of various Cu2+ concentrations within 50 μM was also conducted. As shown in Fig. 7
                        a, the fluorescent intensity of LB-CDs exhibited sensitivity to Cu2+ that decreased with the increase in the Cu2+ concentrations upon excitation at 370 nm. Thus, the sensing system has high sensitivity toward Cu2+ concentration. Fig. 7b illustrates the detection of Cu2+ with linear ranges of 0.05–2.0 μM ((F0 − F)/F0 = 0.18774[Cu2+] − 0.00114, R2 = 0.9964). Furthermore, the detection limit is evaluated to be 12.8 nM (at a signal-to-noise ratio of 3), which could compare favorably with that in the literature (Table 2
                        ). Thus, in comparison with other tests, the developed test is superior, has the benefits of a low limit of detection, and has an extensive linear range.
